The reason SIMD processors are heavily used in signal and image processing is because both of these domains involve repetitive, data-parallel operations â€” exactly what SIMD is built for.
Both signals and images are composed of large sets of data samples that need the same operation applied to each element.
Signal Processing  --> 1D arrays of samples (audio, ECG, sensor data)  -->Filtering, convolution, FFT, correlation
Image Processing   --> 2D arrays of pixels (grayscale or RGB)          -->Filtering, enhancement, compression, transforms

For example:
	â€¢	Every audio sample in a digital filter equation is processed identically.
	â€¢	Every pixel in a brightness adjustment or blur filter undergoes the same computation.
This repetition across elements makes these workloads data-parallel â†’ the ideal case for SIMD.


ðŸ§® Example:C[i] = (A[i] + B[i]) / 2     ;
A 128-bit SIMD register (like NEON or SSE) can blend 16 pixels simultaneously.

